<br>
     Most of you probably don't know me but I have been playing EQ now before Kunark.  I was introduced by an old friend who I spent many hours playing D&amp;D with.  My first roll (1999) was a wizard and I spent a lot of time trolling Graffes and I thought this was one of the best forum sites on the net from content and average intelligence of posts.  I retired from the game in January of 2003 with a 52 wizzy and a 51 shammy.  At the time I gave away my account to a friend who liked to 2 box.  In January of this year I came back and started a Shammy.  I am now at level 53.  I also have a level 25 Necro and a 35 froggy wiz.<br>
<br>
     I was grouped last night in PoJ and this post is based off a long discussion we had.  <br>
<br>
     We were discussing the changes that are do to come out soon and that have been implemented.  Additional XP bonus for groups, AA's, Foci items, spells, etc..  We were all original players having all started with the original Verant EQ before Ruins of Kunark came out.  <br>
<br>
     My question is does anyone else feel that EQ has become diluted to the point of mediocrity.  While the game itself is still fun, in a sort of Diablo'ish sort of way.  Does it not seem as though the shareholder, market driven mindset of Sony has driven the thrill and excitement from the game in order to attract more customers.  <br>
<br>
     While I realize that it is better to be 65 than 6.5 there was and still is a lot of content for all levels of play.  The whole point of EQ I felt was to adventure and to explore.   The thrill of moving deeper, the elements of danger, and the satisfaction of accomplishing a difficult and rewarding quest.  Not just trying to level as fast as you can or trying to build 300 AA points.  Most of the zones go unused because of the race to hit the &quot;high end&quot;. <br>
<br>
     Are there any old timers out there that feel that way.  It used to really mean something to be a high end player.  While all the changes are nice, the game itself has less value as a whole.  The world itself is huge now, but %95 of it goes uncamped.  The reason group play died is because they just made everyone too damn powerful.  Now with group xp bonus they are just making sure that you can go from 1-65 quicker than you can blink.<br>
    <br>
    I almost feel sorry for anyone who starts the game today.   Even though boats were not the funniest I still remember being awed by the sight of the boat going to Kunark and it gave me a chance to chill and chat while waiting for the boat.  The thrills of having to find my gear instead of popping into the bazaar and having it handed to me.  Though at times it did get tedious having to run through WK and Qeynos Hills and Blackburrow to go home to Halas it was still a rich world to see, and there was always people in the zones to meet.   I will never forget having to run from one side of the world to the next because I got tired of waiting for a gate.  Highhold was always fun to run a train through.  Progression has advanced to the point were it is so quick now that they will never see the whole game.  Yes I know you can still play the game anyway you want.  But new players never saw the way we used to play all they know now is PoK books, and KEI's and everything else.<br>
 <br>
     Please don't get me wrong.  I don't hate the game at all, I still enjoy it.  In many ways the changes that were implemented were nice.  To me now it allows me the opportunity to play other classes casually and have fun.  The changes also help bring more casual players into the game letting them enjoy the game more than was previous.  In many ways though I play mostly for nostalgia and to chat with old friends.<br>
<br>
     With all the MMORPG's out there, the niche that was EQ by being different, more difficult has died.  It is getting harder and harder to find reasons to distinguish it from other games.  While I don't plan on playing EQ2 since I think it would be nice to explore some different genres(WoW, I networked all the others).  I think that those of us that were fortunate to have been around during the original &quot;vision&quot; were lucky.  While the game itself, as admitted by Verant, was a fluke in how well it grew and developed was a milestone and an experience that we will find hard to match again.<br>
<br>
Just my 2cp.<br>
<br>
<br>
     Good Hunting,<br>
 <br>
 <br>
     <br>
<br>
  <br>
<br>
<br>
